Now let's start off with a popular analogy which is the foam to drink ratio. You see the liquid alone

22
00:02:37,600 --> 00:02:45,280
represents our real power aka the power that actually gets used to light things up, heat things up or

23
00:02:45,280 --> 00:02:52,400
for example charge your phone's battery. But as you can see that is not all in our glass which in total

24
00:02:52,400 --> 00:02:59,280
represents our apparent power and that is the power your energy provider actually has to deal with in its grid

25
00:02:59,280 --> 00:03:07,280
so that you can get your desired real power. No, we still got the foam which is our reactive power

26
00:03:07,920 --> 00:03:15,840
and truth be told completely useless because it only oscillates between the energy provider and hooked up loads.

27
00:03:16,880 --> 00:03:21,920
Due to it more current flows through the grid than what we actually need for the real power demand

28
00:03:21,920 --> 00:03:29,600
and as you might know for bigger current flow we need thicker wires so that things do not get terribly

29
00:03:29,600 --> 00:03:37,920
inefficient and hot and that of course costs lots of money. So keeping the reactive power close to zero

30
00:03:37,920 --> 00:03:45,760
is our goal here meaning that apparent power should equal the real power. And in the heat gun example we

31
00:03:45,760 --> 00:03:52,960
started with we can actually see such a behaviour that real power equals apparent power meaning it is

32
00:03:52,960 --> 00:03:58,800
definitely possible. Which brings us to the question how such reactive power comes to be.

33
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:06,320
The most popular examples for that are simply a motor and a capacitive power supply that you can

34
00:04:06,320 --> 00:04:14,080
sometimes find in LED lights. Both of them create quite a bit of reactive power in comparison to their real power

35
00:04:14,080 --> 00:04:20,640
power and the root of all evil for that is like I teased at the beginning their current flow.

36
00:04:21,600 --> 00:04:28,640
The power supply ones leads in comparison to the mains voltage and the one from the motor lacks in comparison.

37
00:04:29,520 --> 00:04:34,640
The reason for that are of course the electrical properties of the capacitor for the power supply

38
00:04:35,200 --> 00:04:42,160
and the inductance for the motor coils. But feel free to watch my previous videos about those topics here

39
00:04:42,160 --> 00:04:49,120
so that I can keep the rest of this video short and sweet. Because in a nutshell such phase shifts

40
00:04:49,120 --> 00:04:56,480
do create reactive power. And the simple fix here is to add inductance to the capacitance and vice versa

41
00:04:56,480 --> 00:05:03,680
capacitance to the inductance to get rid of the phase shifts and thus reduce the reactive power

42
00:05:03,680 --> 00:05:11,440
and get a power factor of almost 1. By the way the power factor is simply the real power divided by the

43
00:05:11,440 --> 00:05:18,400
apparent power and thus 1 means real power equals apparent power which is what we are after.

44
00:05:19,440 --> 00:05:25,760
Now like I said one solution is adding capacitance or inductance to the power grid to decrease the

45
00:05:25,760 --> 00:05:33,520
phase shifts and that is actually the first type of a power factor correction circuit and it is called a

46
00:05:33,520 --> 00:05:40,560
passive one. Of course there is also an active one that I already presented to you at the start.

47
00:05:41,440 --> 00:05:47,920
And to understand why we need it let's go back to the current draw of a common power supply I found in my shelf.

