00:05:55,440 --> 00:06:02,640
near the peak of the mains voltage gets. And by doing my usual measurements next we can see that this

50
00:06:02,640 --> 00:06:09,760
current draw creates kind of a lot of reactive power which is easily noticeable through the low power factor.

51
00:06:10,640 --> 00:06:18,480
But there is no phase shift so how does that work? Well the problem here is that this current waveform

52
00:06:18,480 --> 00:06:23,200
can be depicted as a sum of lots of current waveforms with different frequencies.

53
00:06:24,240 --> 00:06:31,920
Most importantly of course is the 50Hz fundamental frequency which is our mains voltage frequency and

54
00:06:31,920 --> 00:06:42,640
it obviously does not feature a phase shift. But then there are also 150Hz, 250Hz, 350Hz and so on parts

55
00:06:43,200 --> 00:06:50,800
which are called 3rd, 5th, 7th and so on current harmonics and they do kind of feature a phase shift

56
00:06:50,800 --> 00:06:58,160
that creates the reactive power. By using my oscilloscope we can actually see how much they matter in comparison

57
00:06:58,160 --> 00:07:05,280
to the fundamental 50Hz frequency and let's just say that they are pretty dominant on the screen here.

58
00:07:06,320 --> 00:07:13,360
So what we can do to fix this problem is basically convert this small current pulse to an even sinusoidal

