00:09:18,720 --> 00:09:23,040
Which now brings us to the question how such an active PFC pulls this off?

77
00:09:24,160 --> 00:09:30,720
Well in a nutshell it does so by increasing the changing mains input voltage into a constant higher

78
00:09:30,720 --> 00:09:39,520
DC voltage voltage that the power supply then uses. Because yes, an active PFC is basically just a glorified

79
00:09:39,520 --> 00:09:47,520
boost converter. You see the problem of normal AC to DC power supplies is that they only draw current near

80
00:09:47,520 --> 00:09:54,000
the voltage peak of the mains voltage because that is when the utilized capacitor's voltage drops beneath

81
00:09:54,000 --> 00:10:02,320
the input voltage and thus can get charged up again. But by supplying a constant boosted voltage this problem

82
00:10:02,320 --> 00:10:09,920
basically disappears. Of course creating such a stable boosted DC voltage from a varying input voltage

83
00:10:09,920 --> 00:10:17,200
is not that easy because you need to monitor the input and output voltage as well as the flowing current

84
00:10:17,200 --> 00:10:23,920
current and then turn on or off the boost converter MOSFET switch accordingly so that always the right

85
00:10:23,920 --> 00:10:31,520
amount of energy gets transferred to the output. When having a look at our practical example then the MOSFET

86
00:10:31,520 --> 00:10:38,560
switching pattern looks something like this with a bigger duty cycle at low input voltages and a smaller

87
00:10:38,560 --> 00:10:47,120
duty cycle at higher input voltages which corresponds with the theory. So all in all such active PFC

88
00:10:47,120 --> 00:10:54,880
are pretty awesome. And considering that there are already regulations in place that limit the created current

